  If a particle (with mass <math|m>) has potential <potential>, then, it's wave function <math|\<psi\><around*|(|\<b-r\>,t|)>> satisfies the Schrödinger equation\ 

  <\equation>
    <frame|\<mathi\>\<hbar\><frac|\<partial\>|\<partial\>t>\<psi\><around*|(|\<b-r\>,t|)>=-<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2m>\<Delta\>\<psi\><around*|(|\<b-r\>,t|)>+<potential>\<psi\><around*|(|\<b-r\>,t|)>.><label|eq:sch-eq-with-potential>
  </equation>

  <paragraph|Case: zero potential>If <math|<potential>=0>, Eq.<nbsp><smart-ref|eq:sch-eq-with-potential> becomes\ 

  <\equation>
    \<mathi\>\<hbar\><frac|\<partial\>|\<partial\>t>\<psi\><around*|(|\<b-r\>,t|)>=-<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2m>\<Delta\>\<psi\><around*|(|\<b-r\>,t|)>.<label|eq:sch-without-potential>
  </equation>

  <\lemma>
    The <with|font-series|bold|general solution> to the free-particle Schrödinger equation<nbsp><smart-ref|eq:sch-without-potential> is:

    <\equation*>
      <boxed|\<psi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>,t|)>=<big|int>A<around|(|<math-bf|k>|)>*e<rsup|<math-up|i><around|(|<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>-\<hbar\>*k<rsup|2>*t/2*m|)>>*\<mathd\><rsup|3>k,>
    </equation*>

    representing a <with|font-series|bold|wave packet> (superposition of plane waves). For a single plane wave, the solution is:

    <\equation*>
      <boxed|\<psi\><rsub|<math-bf|k>><around|(|<math-bf|r>,t|)>=A<around*|(|<math-bf|k>|)> e<rsup|<math-up|i><around|(|<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>-\<hbar\>*k<rsup|2>*t/2*m|)>>.>
    </equation*>

    This describes a particle with definite momentum <math|<math-bf|p>=\<hbar\><math-bf|k>> and energy <math|E=\<hbar\>*\<omega\>=\<hbar\><rsup|2>*k<rsup|2>/2*m>.
  </lemma>

  <\proof>
    Assume the solution can be written as a product of a spatial part and a temporal part:

    <\equation*>
      \<psi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>,t|)>=\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>*T<around|(|t|)>.
    </equation*>

    Substitute into the Schrödinger equation:

    <\equation*>
      <math-up|i>\<hbar\>*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)><frac|\<mathd\>T|\<mathd\>t>=-<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2*m>*T<around|(|t|)>*\<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>.
    </equation*>

    Divide both sides by <math|\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>*T<around|(|t|)>>:

    <\equation*>
      <frac|<math-up|i>\<hbar\>|T<around|(|t|)>>*<frac|\<mathd\>T|\<mathd\>t>=-<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2*m>*<frac|\<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>|\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>>.
    </equation*>

    The left side depends only on <math|t>, and the right side only on <math|<math-bf|r>>. Since they are equal for all <math|<math-bf|r>> and <math|t>, both sides must equal a constant, say <math|E> (the energy):

    <\equation*>
      <frac|<math-up|i>\<hbar\>|T<around|(|t|)>>*<frac|\<mathd\>T|\<mathd\>t>=E,<space|1em>-<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2m>*<frac|\<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>|\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>>=E.
    </equation*>

    <hrule>

    From the time equation:

    <\equation*>
      <frac|\<mathd\>T|\<mathd\>t>=-<frac|<math-up|i>E|\<hbar\>>*T<around|(|t|)>.
    </equation*>

    This is a first-order ODE with solution:

    <\equation*>
      T<around|(|t|)>=e<rsup|-<math-up|i>E*t/\<hbar\>>.
    </equation*>

    <hrule>

    From the spatial equation:

    <\equation*>
      -<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2*m>*\<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=E*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>,
    </equation*>

    or equivalently:

    <\equation*>
      \<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>+k<rsup|2>*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=0,<space|1em><text|where><space|1em>k<rsup|2>=<frac|2*m E|\<hbar\><rsup|2>>.
    </equation*>

    This is the <with|font-series|bold|Helmholtz equation>, whose solutions are <with|font-series|bold|plane waves>:

    <\equation*>
      \<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=e<rsup|<math-up|i><math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>>,
    </equation*>

    where <math|<math-bf|k>> is the wavevector, and <math|<around|\||<math-bf|k>|\|>=k=<sqrt|2*m E>/\<hbar\>>.

    <hrule>

    Combining the time and spatial parts, the general solution is a <with|font-series|bold|superposition of plane waves>:

    <\equation*>
      \<psi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>,t|)>=<big|int>A<around|(|<math-bf|k>|)>*e<rsup|<math-up|i><around|(|<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>-\<omega\>*t|)>>*d<rsup|3>*k,
    </equation*>

    where:\ 

    - <math|A<around|(|<math-bf|k>|)>> is an amplitude determined by initial conditions,\ 

    - The <with|font-series|bold|dispersion relation> is <math|\<omega\>=<frac|E|\<hbar\>>=<frac|\<hbar\>*k<rsup|2>|2*m>>.

    <hrule>

    Check that this satisfies the original equation:

    <\equation*>
      <frac|\<partial\>*\<psi\>|\<partial\>*t>=-<math-up|i>\<omega\>*\<psi\>,<space|1em>\<Delta\>\<psi\>=-k<rsup|2>*\<psi\>.
    </equation*>

    Substitute:

    <\equation*>
      <math-up|i>\<hbar\>*<around|(|-<math-up|i>\<omega\>\<psi\>|)>=-<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>|2*m>*<around|(|-k<rsup|2>*\<psi\>|)>,
    </equation*>

    which simplifies to:

    <\equation*>
      \<hbar\>*\<omega\>*\<psi\>=<frac|\<hbar\><rsup|2>k<rsup|2>|2*m>*\<psi\>,
    </equation*>

    true by the dispersion relation <math|\<omega\>=\<hbar\>k<rsup|2>/2*m>.

    <hrule><label|summary>

    The <with|font-series|bold|general solution> to the free-particle Schrödinger equation is:

    <\equation*>
      <boxed|\<psi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>,t|)>=<big|int>A<around|(|<math-bf|k>|)>*e<rsup|<math-up|i><around|(|<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>-\<hbar\>*k<rsup|2>*t/2*m|)>>*\<mathd\><rsup|3>k,>
    </equation*>

    representing a <with|font-series|bold|wave packet> (superposition of plane waves). For a single plane wave, the solution is:

    <\equation*>
      <boxed|\<psi\><rsub|<math-bf|k>><around|(|<math-bf|r>,t|)>=A<around|(|<math-bf|k>|)>e<rsup|<math-up|i><around|(|<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>-\<hbar\>*k<rsup|2>*t/2*m|)>>.>
    </equation*>

    This describes a particle with definite momentum <math|<math-bf|p>=\<hbar\><math-bf|k>> and energy <math|E=\<hbar\>*\<omega\>=\<hbar\><rsup|2>*k<rsup|2>/2*m>.
  </proof>

  <appendix|Helmholtz equation>

  Helmholtz equation (time–independent part for a free particle):

  <\equation*>
    \<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>+k<rsup|2>*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=0,<space|2em>k=<frac|<sqrt|2*m*E>|\<hbar\>>.
  </equation*>

  Cartesian Laplacian:

  <\equation*>
    \<Delta\>=<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>|\<partial\>*x<rsup|2>>+<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>|\<partial\>*y<rsup|2>>+<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>|\<partial\>*z<rsup|2>>.
  </equation*>

  Because the operator has constant coefficients, its eigenfunctions are exponentials. Therefore, try

  <\equation*>
    \<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=e<rsup|i<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>>=e<rsup|i*<around|(|k<rsub|x>*x+k<rsub|y>*y+k<rsub|z>*z|)>>.
  </equation*>

  Compute derivatives:

  <\equation*>
    <frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>|\<partial\>*x<rsup|2>>*e<rsup|i*k<rsub|x>*x>=<around|(|i*k<rsub|x>|)><rsup|2>*e<rsup|i*k<rsub|x>*x>=-k<rsub|x><rsup|2>*e<rsup|i*k<rsub|x>*x>,
  </equation*>

  and similarly for <math|y,z>. Hence

  <\equation*>
    \<Delta\>\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=-<around|(|k<rsub|x><rsup|2>+k<rsub|y><rsup|2>+k<rsub|z><rsup|2>|)>*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=-<around|\||<math-bf|k>|\|><rsup|2>*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>.
  </equation*>

  Substitute into the Helmholtz equation:

  <\equation*>
    <around*|(|-<around|\||<math-bf|k>|\|><rsup|2>+k<rsup|2>|)>*\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>=0<space|1em>\<Rightarrow\><space|1em><around|\||<math-bf|k>|\|>=k.
  </equation*>

  Fix any scalar <math|C>. The set of points <math|\<b-r\>> that satisfirs

  <\equation*>
    <boxed|<math-bf|k>\<cdot\><math-bf|r>=C>
  </equation*>

  form a <with|font-series|bold|plane> perpendicular to <math|<math-bf|k>>. The phase of <math|\<phi\><around|(|<math-bf|r>|)>> is constant on this plane, and all such planes are parallel and equally spaced by <math|2\<pi\>/<around|\||<math-bf|k>|\|>>. The wavefronts are flat planes, so the function is called a <with|font-series|bold|plane wave>.

  <\remark>
    The wave function is

    <equation*|\<phi\><around*|(|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>|)>=e<rsup|i<with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>>.>

    Its<nbsp><strong|phase><nbsp>is the argument of the exponential:

    <equation*|\<theta\><around*|(|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>|)>=<with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>.>

    This phase depends on the position vector<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>>. Consider a surface where the phase is constant:

    <equation*|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>=C,>

    where<nbsp><math|C><nbsp>is a constant. This equation defines a<nbsp><strong|plane><nbsp>perpendicular to the vector<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>>, since<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>><nbsp>is the normal vector to the plane.

    On this plane, the phase<nbsp><math|\<theta\><around*|(|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>|)>=C><nbsp>is constant. Therefore, the wave function<nbsp><math|\<phi\><around*|(|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>|)>><nbsp>has the same value (up to a complex phase factor) everywhere on the plane. Now consider two parallel planes where the phases differ by<nbsp><math|2\<pi\>>:

    <equation*|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>=C<with|mode|text| \ and \ ><with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>=C+2\<pi\>.>

    The<nbsp><strong|distance><nbsp>between these planes along the direction of<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>><nbsp>is found by projecting the difference onto the unit vector<nbsp><math|<wide|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>|^>=<with|math-font-series|bold|k>/\<mid\><with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<mid\>>:

    <equation*|\<Delta\>r=<frac|2\<pi\>|\<mid\><with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<mid\>>.>

    Thus, the planes of constant phase are<nbsp><strong|equally spaced><nbsp>by a distance<nbsp><math|2\<pi\>/\<mid\><with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<mid\>>. In wave theory, a<nbsp><strong|wavefront><nbsp>is a surface of constant phase. Here, the wavefronts are<nbsp><strong|flat planes><nbsp>perpendicular to<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>>, and they are equally spaced. Because these wavefronts are planes, the wave is called a<nbsp><strong|plane wave>. The phase<nbsp><math|\<theta\><around*|(|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>|)>=<with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>><nbsp>is constant on the planes<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<cdot\><with|math-font-series|bold|r>=C>, which are perpendicular to<nbsp><math|<with|math-font-series|bold|k>>. These planes are parallel and equally spaced by<nbsp><math|2\<pi\>/\<mid\><with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<mid\>>, forming flat wavefronts. Hence,<nbsp><math|\<phi\><around*|(|<with|math-font-series|bold|r>|)>><nbsp>is a<nbsp><strong|plane wave>.

    <equation*|<frame|<with|math-level|0|math-display|false|<with|math-level|0|math-display|false|<with|math-level|0|math-display|true|<frac|2\<pi\>|\<mid\><with|math-font-series|bold|k>\<mid\>>>>>>>
  </remark>

